1 lived in Clark County and the five nearby rural counties, whereas
2 today these counties are home to more than 2.3 million people; and
3 WHEREAS, Underground testing of explosive nuclear weapons
4 could inadvertently release radioactive material into the air, as has
5 happened in the past with at least 32 venting accidents from
6 underground tests at the Nevada Test Site, including the 1970
7 Baneberry incident, which released a significant amount of
8 radioactive material across a widespread area of the western United
9 States and exposed 86 Nevada Test Site workers to high levels of
10 radiation; and
11 WHEREAS, More than 32,000 “Downwinder” claims have been
12 filed as a result of atmospheric testing, and more than 27,000 claims
13 have been filed under the Energy Employees Occupational Illness
14 Compensation Program Act by former Nevada Test Site employees
15 and contractors, demonstrating the impact of nuclear testing on the
16 health of Nevadans; and
17 WHEREAS, Exposure to radiation from resumed testing of
18 explosive nuclear weapons could result in negative chronic health
19 effects to the local population over time, including cancer, heart
20 disease, neurological disorders, autoimmune disorders and thyroid
21 disease; and
22 WHEREAS, Previous underground testing of explosive nuclear
23 weapons caused tremors in Las Vegas registering as high as 5.7 on
24 the Richter scale, which rattled residents and visitors, underscoring
25 that resumed testing could pose significant risks to the
26 infrastructure, buildings and, ultimately, economy of Nevada,
27 including its tourism and real estate industries; and
28 WHEREAS, Resumed explosive nuclear testing would further
29 contaminate local groundwater sources, as evidenced by the
30 environmental reports of the National Nuclear Security
31 Administration indicating radioactive materials in groundwater from
32 previous testing and the known effectiveness of groundwater in
33 dispersing radioactive contamination into the surrounding
34 environment; and
35 WHEREAS, There is no technical or military requirement to
36 resume nuclear testing, as the Directors of the Los Alamos, Sandia
37 and Lawrence Livermore National Laboratories and the Commander
38 of United States Strategic Command, along with the Secretaries of
39 Defense and Energy, have annually affirmed the safety, security,
40 reliability and performance of nuclear weapons for over 25 years
41 and have consistently determined there is no technical or military
42 requirement to resume testing; and
43 WHEREAS, No country other than North Korea has conducted an
44 explosive nuclear test this century, and 187 countries, including the
45 United States, every NATO and United States Pacific ally, Russia
-
